# My favorite Erlang Program by Joe Armstrong in Elixir

```elixir
Mix.install([
  {:kino, "~> 0.19.0"}
])
```

## Intro

In [this blog post](https://joearms.github.io/published/2013-11-21-My-favorite-erlang-program.html) Joe Armstrong walks through a simple example of Erlang code to demonstrate the power and simplicity of Erlang processes.

This Livebook translates the code to Elixir.

## Universal Server

First we define a new module `UniversalServer` with only a single function  called server `server`.
The function waits for an incoming message, via the `receive` block, and expects this message to be a two-element tuple `{:become, func}` with `func` being a zero-argument function.

As soon as this message containing the function is received, the function will be called, effectively handing the full control of the current process to this function.

```elixir
defmodule UniversalServer do
  def server do
    # Set Label for debugging
    Process.set_label(__MODULE__)
    # wait for an incoming message
    receive do
      # expect the message to be of the format {:become func}
      {:become, func} when is_function(func, 0) ->
        # call func
        func.()
    end
  end
end
```

<!-- livebook:{"output":true} -->

```
{:module, UniversalServer, <<70, 79, 82, 49, 0, 0, 6, ...>>, ...}
```

## Factorial Server

Next we define another module `FactorialServer` with another zero-argument function `server`. This `server` function also uses a `receive` block for waiting for an incoming tuple message.
This tuple is expected to contain a process id (PID) `from` as first element and an integer as second element.

Uppon receiving such message the factorial of the given integer is calculated and the send to the processed indicated by the `from` address.

```elixir
defmodule FactorialServer do
  def server do
    # Set Label for debugging
    Process.set_label(__MODULE__)
    # wait for an incoming message
    receive do
      # expect the message to be of format {pid, int}
      {from, n} when is_pid(from) and is_integer(n) ->
        # calculate factorial and send the result back to the from-adress
        send(from, factorial(n))
        # recursive call to wait for the next message
        server()
    end
  end

  def factorial(0), do: 1
  def factorial(n), do: factorial(n - 1) * n
end
```

<!-- livebook:{"output":true} -->

```
{:module, FactorialServer, <<70, 79, 82, 49, 0, 0, 8, ...>>, ...}
```

## Spawing the Server

Now we can spawn a new process and let it calculate the factorial of some number.
First we spawn the universal server and capture the PID of the new process in a variable.
This universal server will just idle and wait for our initial message.
Remember this message is expected to look like `{:become, func}` to tell the server what code to execute.

So next we send such message to the pid, passing the `FactorialServer.server` function as second tuple element. This will cause the `UniversalServer` to run the factorial server function.

The `FactorialServer.server` in turn will wait for the next message, expecting it to be a tuple ` {from, n}`. `from` is the PID of the process that shall receive the resul of the calculation.

So the next message we send is `{self(), 50}`. This instructs the server process to calculate the factorial of 50 and to send the result back to us.

Finally we use a `receive` block to wait for the result to be received and then print it.

```elixir
# spawn new process running the UniversalServer
pid = spawn(&UniversalServer.server/0)
# send the FactorialServer function to be run inside the other process
send(pid, {:become, &FactorialServer.server/0})
# send the number 50 to the server for it to calculate the result 
send(pid, {self(), 50})

# receive the result
receive do
  # print it
  result ->
    IO.inspect(result, label: "Result")
end
```

<!-- livebook:{"output":true} -->

```
Result: 120
```

<!-- livebook:{"output":true} -->

```
120
```

Due to recursive structure of the server function it can handle multiple requests in order. This allows us to send further requests to the same server.

```elixir
# send another number to the same server
send(pid, {self(), 5})

# receive the result again
receive do
  # print it
  result ->
    IO.inspect(result, label: "Result")
end

Kino.nothing()
```

<!-- livebook:{"output":true} -->

```
Result: 6
```

## Trace Process Communication

We can use `Kino.Process.render_seq_trace` to plot the process communication in a sequence diagram.
Observe how the two messages are send to the pid and the result is received.

We limit the scope of the tracing the messages from and to the server process to see only the 3 messages we care about from all the messages traveling through the virtual machine.

```elixir
server_pid = spawn(&UniversalServer.server/0)

Kino.Process.seq_trace(
  # trace only messages from and to the server_pid
  [server_pid],
  fn ->
    # spawn new process running the UniversalServer
    # send the FactorialServer function to be run inside the other process
    send(server_pid, {:become, &FactorialServer.server/0})
    # send the number 50 to the server for it to calculate the result 
    send(server_pid, {self(), 3})

    # receive the result
    receive do
      # print it
      result -> IO.inspect(result, label: "Output")
    end

    # send another number to the server
    send(server_pid, {self(), 5})

    # receive the result again
    receive do
      # print it
      result ->
        IO.inspect(result, label: "Output")
    end
  end,
  caption: "Sequence Diagram of messages",
  # stringify the message and escape hashtag for cleaner output
  message_label: &{:ok, inspect(&1) |> String.replace("#", "#35;")}
)
|> elem(1)
```

<!-- livebook:{"output":true} -->

```
Output: 120
Output: 6
```

<!-- livebook:{"output":true} -->

```mermaid
%%{init: {'themeCSS': '.actor:last-of-type:not(:only-of-type) {dominant-baseline: hanging;}'} }%%
sequenceDiagram
participant 0 AS self();
participant 1 AS FactorialServer<br/><0.2940.0>;
0->>1: {:become, &FactorialServer.server/0}
0->>1: {#35;PID<0.2537.0>, 3}
1->>0: 6

```

Now lets try to widen the scope of the tracing and see what other messages are sent and received.

Notice that now there are three processes visible. The third process is the one responsible for handling IO. when calling `IO.inspect` for printing the result value the string to be printed is sent as message to this process and a confirmation is sent back.

```elixir
server_pid = spawn(&UniversalServer.server/0)

Kino.Process.seq_trace(
  # trace all messages
  :all,
  fn ->
    # spawn new process running the UniversalServer
    # send the FactorialServer function to be run inside the other process
    send(server_pid, {:become, &FactorialServer.server/0})
    # send the number 50 to the server for it to calculate the result 
    send(server_pid, {self(), 5})

    # receive the result
    receive do
      # print it
      result -> IO.inspect(result, label: "Output")
    end
  end,
  caption: "Sequence Diagram of messages",
  # stringify the message and escape hashtag for cleaner output
  message_label:
    &{:ok,
     inspect(&1, pretty: true, width: 30)
     |> String.replace("\n", "<br>")
     |> String.replace("#", "#35;")}
)
|> elem(1)
```

<!-- livebook:{"output":true} -->

```
Output: 6
```

<!-- livebook:{"output":true} -->

