sequenceDiagram
participant 0 AS self();
participant 1 AS FactorialServer<br/><0.2901.0>;
0->>1: {:become,<br> &FactorialServer.server/0}
0->>1: {#35;PID<0.2537.0>, 5}
1->>0: 120

```

## Multiple messages

We can also send multiple requests one after another before processing the results:

```elixir
Kino.Process.seq_trace(
  # trace only messages from and to the server_pid
  [server_pid],
  fn ->
    # send 3 requests
    send(server_pid, {self(), 3})
    send(server_pid, {self(), 4})
    send(server_pid, {self(), 5})

    # receive 3 results
    receive do: (result -> IO.inspect(result, label: "Output"))
    receive do: (result -> IO.inspect(result, label: "Output"))
    receive do: (result -> IO.inspect(result, label: "Output"))
  end,
  caption: "Sequence Diagram of messages",
  # stringify the message and escape hashtag for cleaner output
  message_label: &{:ok, inspect(&1) |> String.replace("#", "#35;")}
)
|> elem(1)
```

<!-- livebook:{"output":true} -->

```
Output: 24
Output: 120
Output: 6
```

<!-- livebook:{"output":true} -->

```mermaid
%%{init: {'themeCSS': '.actor:last-of-type:not(:only-of-type) {dominant-baseline: hanging;}'} }%%
sequenceDiagram
participant 0 AS self();
participant 1 AS FactorialServer<br/><0.2901.0>;
0->>1: {#35;PID<0.2537.0>, 3}
0->>1: {#35;PID<0.2537.0>, 4}
0->>1: {#35;PID<0.2537.0>, 5}
1->>0: 6
1->>0: 24
1->>0: 120

```

## Stateful Server

Being functional languages with immutable data structures it seems impossible for Erlang and Elixir to do any stateful computation.

Lets take a look at how processes can be used to store state and provide an interface to read and manipulate some state.

This is how all state in all Erlang and Elixir application is managed at its core. Everything else is just abstraction built around it.

The core idea is to keep some value stored in a local variable alive by passing it as parameter through an recursive function without a base case, causing effectively an infinite recursion that never halts.
This allows the value to be modified - or rather the argument to be replaced - at each recursive step.

But this alone would just lead to an infinite recursive calculation that never halts but would be useless.

The next important piece in the puzzle is to inject a `receive` block into the recursive function to wait for incoming messages from other processes. This slows down the calculation by doing only one recursion-step for each received message, forcing the function to idle in-between. 
Additionally it allows the recursive function to adjust the exact recursion step based on the incoming message from the outside.

The primary difference to our `FactorialServer` above is that the server function will now expect one instead of no arguments.

Lets see it in action:

```elixir
defmodule StateServer do
  # a recursive function with a single argument
  def server(state) do
    Process.set_label(__MODULE__)
    # instead of doing the recursive call immediately,
    # we wait for an incoming message.
    # each recursive call below leads back to this receive block.
    receive do
      # if the received message is {:write, ...}
      {:write, new_state} ->
        # recursive call with new state value
        server(new_state)

      # if the message is {:update, ...} and a single-argument function is provided
      {:update, func} when is_function(func, 1) ->
        # pass the current state the to function 
        # and pass the resulting value to the recursive call
        server(func.(state))

      # if the message is :read and a process id is provided
      {:read, from} when is_pid(from) ->
        # send the current state to the process id
        send(from, {:ok, state})
        # recursive call to keep old state alive
        server(state)
    end
  end
end
```

<!-- livebook:{"output":true} -->

```
{:module, StateServer, <<70, 79, 82, 49, 0, 0, 7, ...>>, ...}
```

Now lets spawn the recursive function is separate process.

```elixir
# spawn the function as processes, providing 24 as initial argument
# and capture the process id into a variable
state_server_pid = spawn(StateServer, :server, [24])

# the function/process will immediatly idle waiting for an incoming message

# send the :read message to the process
send(state_server_pid, {:read, self()})

# we expect the process to reply with the current value
receive do
  # we receive the value (expect it to be 24) and print it
  {:ok, value} -> IO.inspect(value, label: "Current State")
end

# send the next message to the process.
# this will alter the recursion step in the process to pass 23 as new argument
send(state_server_pid, {:write, 23})

# send :read again
send(state_server_pid, {:read, self()})

# and receive the response
receive do
  # now we expect value to be 23
  {:ok, value} -> IO.inspect(value, label: "Current State")
end

# send :update and a lambda function to modify the current value
send(state_server_pid, {:update, fn old -> old * 2 end})

# send :read to query for the new value
send(state_server_pid, {:read, self()})

# receive the response
receive do
  # expected to be 23*2 = 46
  {:ok, value} -> IO.inspect(value, label: "Current State")
end
```

<!-- livebook:{"output":true} -->

```
Current State: 24
Current State: 23
Current State: 46
```

<!-- livebook:{"output":true} -->

```
46
```

Lets plot the correspondign sequence diagram again:

```elixir
state_server_pid = spawn(StateServer, :server, [24])

Kino.Process.seq_trace(
  # trace only the messages from and to the server
  [state_server_pid],
  fn ->
    send(state_server_pid, {:read, self()})

    receive do
      {:ok, value} -> IO.inspect(value, label: "Current State")
    end

    send(state_server_pid, {:write, 23})

    send(state_server_pid, {:read, self()})

    receive do
      {:ok, value} -> IO.inspect(value, label: "Current State")
    end

    send(state_server_pid, {:update, fn old -> old * 2 end})

    send(state_server_pid, {:read, self()})

    receive do
      {:ok, value} -> IO.inspect(value, label: "Current State")
    end
  end,
  caption: "Sequence Diagram of messages",
  # stringify the message and escape hashtag for cleaner output
  message_label:
    &{:ok,
     inspect(&1, pretty: true, width: 30)
     |> String.replace("\n", "<br>")
     |> String.replace("#", "#35;")}
)
|> elem(1)
```

<!-- livebook:{"output":true} -->

```
Current State: 24
Current State: 23
Current State: 46
```

